Easiest way is to pass a callback listener to the adapter

````
// in your adapter
var storyClickedListener: ((story: Story) -&gt; Unit)? = null

// in your item click listener
holder.cardview.setOnClickListener {
    // if there&#39;s a listener, call it and pass the clicked Story
    storyClickedListener?.invoke(dataSet[position])
}
````

Then in your Activity or whatever, pass a listener function to the Adapter which does whatever you need to do:

````
storiesAdapter.storyClickedListener = { story -&gt;
    // react to the click
}
````

That way the adapter doesn&#39;t need to know anything about the Activity it&#39;s inside (and it shouldn&#39;t really) - it just has a listener it can inform when an event happens. The owner of the listener handles the details of what happens in response.

The classic Java way to do this would be with an interface - create an interface with a callback function, make the Activity implement it, pass the Activity to the Adapter as an instance of `YourCallbackInterface` so it can call that listener function. Same thing, but wih Kotlin you can just pass a function like this, nice and simple!

Also you don&#39;t *need* to pass a `Story` as a parameter, but usually you&#39;d want to pass some info about what&#39;s been clicked

