`|` is the bitwise OR operator. You want `&amp;&amp;`, the logical AND operator. &quot;If `number2` is greater than `number1` **and** `number3` is greater than `number1`.&quot; Also, you don&#39;t want any `if` on the last `else`, since by then you&#39;ve ruled out two of the three possibilities and there&#39;s only one possibility left.

Separately, we&#39;ll want to handle the case where `number1` and `number2` are the same, and they&#39;re both lower than `number3`. That can be done by using `&gt;=` instead of `&gt;` in the first `if`.

So:

    if (number2 &gt;= number1 &amp;&amp; number3 &gt; number1) {
        // ^^^
        minimum = number1;
    } else if (number1 &gt; number2 &amp;&amp; number3 &gt; number2) {
        // ^^
        minimum = number2;
    } else /* No `if` here */ {
        minimum = number3;
    }

JavaScript example (since the logic and syntax of the above is common to both Java and JavaScript):

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: true console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    function test(number1, number2, number3) {
        let minimum;
        if (number2 &gt;= number1 &amp;&amp; number3 &gt; number1) {
            // ^^^
            minimum = number1;
        } else if (number1 &gt; number2 &amp;&amp; number3 &gt; number2) {
            // ^^
            minimum = number2;
        } else /* No `if` here */ {
            minimum = number3;
        }
        console.log(minimum);
    }

    test(1, 2, 3); // Should be 1
    test(3, 2, 1); // Should be 1
    test(2, 2, 1); // Should be 1
    test(2, 2, 4); // Should be 2


